From him he learnt to avoid the error of sacrificing every thing to effect, and wisely tempered the natural impetuosity of his own mind. That Sophocles could have been equally grand with AEschylus is certain, but he preferred elegance of sen- timent and correctness of rhythm to the more imposing mag- nificence of his friend.
